me>Bradley</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE010482%2F1"><gtr:id>E996D10F-F9C1-4B8B-86C2-59D6F5A4FE84</gtr:id><gtr:title>Poverty, Philanthropy and the State: the University Settlements and the Urban Working Classes, 1918 - 1960</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E010482/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>University settlements - such as Toynbee Hall in East London - are historically interesting institutions in their own right. But they also provide exceptional insights into a range of important historical and contemporary questions about disadvantaged urban communities, life courses, social inclusion and social exclusion. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Dr Katharine Bradley looked at the university settlement movement in the period 1918 - 1960 for her doctoral thesis, as a case study of the relationship between charities and state welfare in the interwar years. In this period, the voluntary sector developed pioneering ways of addressing social need which the state later adopted during this crucial period of change and development. This was an important feature of the mixed economy of welfare in the interwar and early post-Second World War period. Dr Bradley also explored the ways in which members of local communities used charities and settlements, and attitudes towards volunteering and citizenship, during a time of immense change and upheaval. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Her work focusses in particular on youth work, adult education, juvenile delinquency and the early youth courts and healthcare. During her postdoctoral year, Dr Bradley will be working on a monograph based on her doctoral work, which explores and expands these themes.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>25954</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>34F7A426-AE09-400E-89D7-520859C6A8AF</gtr:id><gtr:title>Juvenile Delinquency, the Juvenile Courts and the Settlement Movement 1908-1950: Basil Henriques and Toynbee Hall</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Twentieth Century British History</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/f0f22c67af4c0afbe6f80981185f49cb"><gtr:id>f0f22c67af4c0afbe6f80981185f49cb</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bradley K</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2007-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa0fa04c6779b</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>81D2F9C1-1CFB-47E2-8927-9B6B1A4C2E92</gtr:id><gtr:title>'Growing up with a City': Exploring Settlement Youth Work in London and Chicago,
 
